WEBVTT

00:09.616 --> 00:15.764
What's the value to a scientist to be established 
at an institution like Scripps? A value to a

00:15.784 --> 00:17.486
scientist? Right. Let me, the question's poorly 
phrased. Usually you think of a scientist working

00:21.452 --> 00:29.542
out of a very traditional department, that is, 
department of geophysics or what have you. But

00:30.023 --> 00:33.828
here there seems to be a mixture of scientists 
working in and around the ocean. Is that a

00:33.848 --> 00:36.231
particular value to a scientist doing research?

00:39.130 --> 00:56.066
Well, I think

00:39.130 --> 00:56.066
sometimes, yes, the value, I think, is from the 
sharing of information from various

00:39.130 --> 00:56.066
disciplines. So that a scientist that scripts, 
and I think this is true in general of

00:58.408 --> 01:08.378
oceanographic institution, is that the science 
is not as compartmentalize in oceanography as it

01:08.695 --> 01:29.560
might be in a more traditional university where 
you have departments of physics, chemistry,

01:08.695 --> 01:29.560
mathematics, in which a man might

01:08.695 --> 01:29.560
carry out his entire scientific career in one 
fairly narrow field. Oceanography doesn't have

01:30.081 --> 01:36.829
these sharp boundaries, and when One sees that 
right from the beginning when you go to sea and

01:37.535 --> 01:45.305
share the use of a ship with many other 
disciplines. And so that, in a sense, is an

01:46.406 --> 01:49.670
advantage. It's a broadening experience to work 
in an oceanographic institution. Now, were you

01:57.801 --> 02:01.405
the driving force behind the Operation Mid-Pack? 
I wouldn't say I was the driving force. I think The

02:07.319 --> 02:10.804
most important person in MIDPAC was Roger Bell. He 
was the leader of the expedition. I was, my

02:13.948 --> 02:22.159
function, I remember, I was chairman of what they 
called a joint planning committee. We had the, we

02:22.439 --> 02:27.666
wanted to have a two-ship expedition.

02:30.069 --> 02:36.077
That was mainly my interest because I wanted to do 
seismic refreshment work before I had a two-ship.

02:36.631 --> 02:41.175
Scripps Institution only had one ocean-going 
ship. That was the Horizon. There was a similar

02:45.059 --> 02:58.131
interest in doing oceanographic

02:45.059 --> 02:58.131
exploration, geophysical, at the Naval 
Electronics Lab. So we got together. This was

03:00.754 --> 03:04.377
largely through the efforts of Roger Revelle. and 
formed a joint expedition of the two

03:06.382 --> 03:10.646
laboratories. And my function there was to be 
chairman of a committee where we met about once a

03:11.847 --> 03:22.937
week for several months before the cruise to 
discuss what we were going to do.

03:30.343 --> 03:35.848
Was the Mid-Pac Expedition related to the later 
Nor-Pac Expedition? I don't believe so, except

03:36.655 --> 03:39.199
the name.

03:41.842 --> 03:47.310
NORPAC was an area describing an expedition 
studying the North Pacific. The MIDPAC was

03:48.291 --> 03:52.337
studying the Mid-Pacific. But I don't believe 
they were too directly related. I had nothing to do

03:55.902 --> 03:57.825
with NORPAC. What sort of information about the

04:06.372 --> 04:12.478
Well, there were a variety of projects done. It's 
hard for me to remember all of the things that were

04:13.458 --> 04:18.343
done. There were several projects studying the 
morphology of the ocean bottom through echo

04:18.363 --> 04:25.429
sounding. We were doing studies of ocean bottom 
structures through seismic refraction methods.

04:36.494 --> 04:40.741
expedition to study heat flow also. Of course, 
bottom coring was very important. The first time

04:46.430 --> 04:58.729
we used the piston core, we had a kind of a new device 
at that time developed by Kuhlenberg, a Swedish

04:46.430 --> 04:58.729
oceanographer. So we had piston cores. We had 
gravity cores. and taking samples of the

05:04.405 --> 05:12.996
seafloor, taking temperature probes, and a 
variety of things. It would be hard for me just

05:13.016 --> 05:28.557
informally like this to really summarize the 
whole thing, but in a way it was a model for many

05:13.016 --> 05:28.557
expeditions to come later on, like Capricorn and 
other expeditions. That was exactly what I was

05:29.380 --> 05:34.648
interested in, was this idea of it being a model for 
later expeditions, how it's usually

05:29.380 --> 05:34.648
characterized. What did it do in your particular 
research? What direction did it take you after

05:37.352 --> 05:39.376
mid-pack? Oh, I think it demonstrated, let's say 
it demonstrated for us for the first time that we

05:41.279 --> 05:56.282
could go out and do, use seismic refraction 
methods to let's say to learn about the structure

05:57.055 --> 06:25.324
of down to the upper mantle and so it there was quite 
a lot of new information

05:57.055 --> 06:25.324
gained in mid-pack which certainly justified us 
continuing it to other oceans other parts of the

05:57.055 --> 06:25.324
ocean to see if what we learned on MITPAC was 
typical of the ocean, and what the differences of

06:25.760 --> 06:35.513
similarities were. So in that sense, the success 
of MITPAC did stimulate work and the continuing

06:36.575 --> 06:48.711
work in my field as well as in many other fields. 
It's really like the study of... of the heat flow

06:54.228 --> 06:57.051
from the ocean bottom, for example. The initial 
results on mid-pack were very important in

06:58.072 --> 07:10.746
encouraging further work in that field.

