08:16.855 --> 08:21.981
Would you explain what elastic anastrophe is? 
Anisotropy. Is it anisoptery? Anisotropy.

08:26.660 --> 08:26.780
Right. Yeah, well, that's really part. Let's see, 
I guess you're referring to something which is

08:29.443 --> 08:40.937
really part of this study I'm mentioning of the 
ocean bottom structure. In that study, we measure

08:40.957 --> 08:49.487
the velocity of the waves under the ocean bottom.

08:50.648 --> 09:12.037
The objective of this work has always been mainly 
to achieve penetration through the crustal

08:50.648 --> 09:12.037
rocks, which form sort of a thin veneer over the 
bulk of the earth, to penetrate through that crust

08:50.648 --> 09:12.037
into the real earth material, the mantle. The 
great bulk of the earth is called the mantle.

09:14.701 --> 09:19.828
That's the solid exterior of the earth that's 
about 3,000 to 4,000 kilometers thick and lies

09:20.399 --> 09:29.368
above the molten core.

09:32.651 --> 09:44.443
We found that the velocity of this mantle, the 
upper part of the mantle right below the crust,

09:32.651 --> 09:44.443
that its velocity depended on direction of 
travel.

09:47.125 --> 09:49.748
And in other words, it was not isotropic. 
Isotropic means that the properties are the same

09:51.179 --> 09:58.210
regardless of what direction, but it's 
anisotropic. And a good deal of our work here in the

10:00.173 --> 10:16.680
last few years has been studying this anisotropy, 
attempting to measure it and, if possible, learn

10:00.173 --> 10:16.680
something about what causes it. Well, why did you 
hypothesize about the upper mantle of the ocean in

10:18.280 --> 10:24.305
terms of exhibiting it? Was there any clue you had 
that the upper mantle might exhibit this? The idea

10:29.650 --> 10:39.819
that it was anisotropic came not from our work, but 
from other people. The principal one here is Harry

10:39.879 --> 10:47.005
Hess, who studied anisotropy of the rocks that are 
believed to be typical of the rocks that come from

10:48.098 --> 10:56.828
the upper mantle. He was a geologist, one of his 
specialties. He was a very broad-thinking

11:02.335 --> 11:11.666
geologist, but one of his specialties was 
studying these rocks in a microscope. These were

11:11.686 --> 11:17.953
samples of rocks that came from various places 
where it was believed that they were extruded by

11:18.322 --> 11:23.770
volcanic process from deep down in the earth, and 
therefore represented . Those, when you look at

11:24.671 --> 11:42.757
them in a microscope, you can see that the grains in 
a specimen, say a small specimen of the size of a few

11:24.671 --> 11:42.757
centimeters, that the grains in that specimen are 
not oriented at random, but are lined up. And this

11:44.139 --> 11:46.422
interested him all Many years ago, he studied this 
anisotropy

11:46.823 --> 11:58.362
in the little sample. And so

11:59.905 --> 12:11.464
he was aware of this anisotropy in small samples, 
the thing that was startling about this

12:12.170 --> 12:42.109
anisotropy was that it occurred over long 
distances hundreds of thousands of miles lined up

12:12.170 --> 12:42.109
in order it wasn't surprising to anybody that 
you'd find this anisotropy in a small material

12:12.170 --> 12:42.109
because the crystals that make up the uh the type of 
material that forms the earth crest are

12:12.170 --> 12:42.109
anisotropic crystals the crystals are not don't 
have a simple cubical structure, but have a more

12:42.730 --> 12:48.676
complex structure. So both the index of 
refraction, that's the speed of light through the

12:48.696 --> 13:09.636
crystal, and the speed of sound, speed of elastic 
waves, both of these depend on the direction of

12:48.696 --> 13:09.636
propagation through the crystal. So if the 
crystals then are lined up, over a long distance,

13:13.696 --> 13:27.951
then you get an effect of velocity being in 
different directions, similar to what we observe

13:13.696 --> 13:27.951
in our seismic experiment. Well, how is this 
related to sea floor spreading?

13:34.498 --> 13:43.467
There is an experimental relation

13:44.459 --> 13:59.653
we have found is that the direction

13:44.459 --> 13:59.653
of maximum velocity is in the direction that sea 
floor was spreading at the time the rock was

13:44.459 --> 13:59.653
formed. So the obvious conclusion here is that the 
process of the rock being formed at the time the

14:00.854 --> 14:13.926
ocean bottom was spreading apart In the process of 
formation, the crystals are lined up. Now, the

14:19.708 --> 14:30.725
details of how this happened are not known, but 
there's a clue to that in the observation that the

14:19.708 --> 14:30.725
maximum direction of maximum velocity is in the 
direction of spreading.

14:33.470 --> 14:42.023
And we observed that first in the area right off 
California, where the sea is bottom that's

14:42.273 --> 14:47.021
directly west of here is formed by east-west 
spreading, roughly. It's not exactly east-west.

14:51.528 --> 14:59.540
And we've found that when we first observed this, 
that the maximum velocity was roughly east-west.

15:00.202 --> 15:05.530
And it turns out that if we compare it in detail with 
the estimated the direction of spreading. Then it

15:08.746 --> 15:33.041
agrees almost exactly at 90 degrees by making its 
first statistical study of all of the stations

15:08.746 --> 15:33.041
within the area and comparing the velocity with 
its direction with the direction of

15:08.746 --> 15:33.041
the direction that it was moving at the time it was 
formed. You understand? So this is all fairly

15:37.201 --> 15:41.127
recent, too. It's all in the process of...

15:47.457 --> 15:56.751
In fact, we have a paper in the press right now 
that's just being submitted to the Geophysical

15:47.457 --> 15:56.751
Research Letter giving the latest study of what 
I'm talking about here. So it's a fairly complex

15:58.073 --> 16:04.282
study, and it's going on now, isn't it? And all the 
answers aren't in yet. But this has been generally

16:06.563 --> 16:10.889
the continuous direction of your work the last 
several years? Yeah, anisotropy is part of it. The

16:15.236 --> 16:29.157
study of, the whole study of structure, say the 
velocity structure and how it's related to the

16:15.236 --> 16:29.157
geology of the area is continuing also. 
